0jGe-wBe0RgS3hBJSAQO-svwNG54WbADvzHROW8-MnyRyvC1E=\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering class loading**\\n\\nI'm thinking about using Class.forName with an unknown name in native code, and how it might interact with a custom loader. If the custom loadClass method can return an existing class, then it's quite possible that I wouldn’t need to define anything dynamically. It raises interesting questions about class management and how that impacts performance and behavior in different scenarios. Let me explore this further!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining class loading logic**\\n\\nI’m diving into class loading details, specifically how to override the `loadClass` method. The method `Class.forName(name, true, loader)` probably relies on `loadClass(name)` which is interesting. The public `loadClass` method calls `loadClass(name, false)`, and the VM might call `loadClass(String)`.\\n\\nI need to manage both public and protected versions of `loadClass`, which complicates things. I’m considering whether `resolveClass` should be called or if it could throw an error. There’s a lot to sort through!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Implementing class loading**\\n\\nI’m focusing on how to implement the `loadClass` method with an override. I plan to check if an alias exists in the `aliases` map, and return it if found; otherwise, I'll call the superclass's `loadClass`. \\n\\nThere could be a challenge with `Class.forName` not accepting an alias if it looks for an existing class with a different name, which could lead to test failures. I think I can create a test that ensures the proper exception is thrown if an alias isn’t found. That feels like a solid approach!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering coverage integration**\\n\\nI’m contemplating whether “add high coverage integration” would prefer that the tests succeed. Still, I can stick to the rules, which are supposed to be version-agnostic. This approach will account for overloaded `Class.forName`. I realize that if the first attempt fails, the second can still be executed, eliminating the need for a custom implementation. It feels good to keep things straightforward while ensuring coverage with these options!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_RYdsZP6YGmsUvAzBSU0ulrF7|fc_0c3f87fa662cfb580169f14f4fccac819cb916375ca23bccc9", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.apache.seata/seata-all/2.1.0/user-code-filter.json", "limit": 200}, "partialJson": "{\"path\":\"tests/src/org.apache.seata/seata-all/2.1.0/user-code-filter.json\",\"limit\":200}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1634, "output": 2582, "cacheRead": 15872, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 20088, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777422124170, "responseId": "resp_0c3f87fa662cfb580169f14f2c9cb0819c8065bb72c94ffac2"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_RYdsZP6YGmsUvAzBSU0ulrF7|fc_0c3f87fa662cfb580169f14f4fccac819cb916375ca23bccc9", "toolName": "read", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "{\n  \"rules\": [\n    {\n      \"excludeClasses\": \"**\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"includeClasses\": \"io.seata.**\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"includeClasses\": \"org.apache.seata.**\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"includeClasses\": \"org_apache_seata.seata_all.**\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n"}], "isError": false, "timestamp": 1777422160344}]}
